# Conventional Commits and Versioning

## How versioning works

- Use **conventional commits** on all commits so that when release automation is added, versioning will work correctly.
- When release workflows are added: every merge to `main` can trigger a release (version from commits since last tag); every PR can run a version-check that comments with the version preview.

## Commit types → version bump

| Commit type | Bump |
|-------------|------|
| `feat:` | **Minor** (0.1.0 → 0.2.0) |
| `fix:`, `perf:` | **Patch** (0.1.0 → 0.1.1) |
| `docs:`, `chore:`, `refactor:`, `test:`, `ci:`, `build:` | **Patch** (by default; configurable) |
| `feat!:` or body with `BREAKING CHANGE:` | **Major** (0.1.0 → 1.0.0) |

Use the correct type so the next version is computed correctly. Scopes are optional but help (e.g. `feat(api):`, `fix(cli):`).

## Required for versioning

- **Conventional Commits format** on all commits that will be merged to `main` (subject line: `type(scope): description` or `type: description`).
- When a version-check workflow is added, do not merge until it passes.

## Workflows (when added)

- **`.github/workflows/release.yml`**: On push to `main`, can run `python-semantic-release`, bump version, tag, and create a GitHub release.
- **`.github/workflows/version-check.yml`**: On PR to `main`, can validate conventional commits and comment with the version preview.
- Config: `[tool.semantic_release]` in `pyproject.toml` when using python-semantic-release.

## References

- [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/)
- [python-semantic-release](https://python-semantic-release.readthedocs.io/) (optional, for automated versioning)
